Package sk.stuba.fiit.martin.szabo.hashtable.hashtable

Class Hashtable

  • java.lang.Object
    • sk.stuba.fiit.martin.szabo.hashtable.hashtable.Hashtable
  • Direct Known Subclasses:
    HashtableOpenAddressing, HashtableSeparateChaining
    public abstract class Hashtable
extends java.lang.Object
    The Hashtable class provides an abstract data type for a hash table that maps keys to values. It implements the hash table using an ArrayList of Objects. The class is abstract, so it needs to be extended by another class that implements the resolveCollision(int, java.lang.Object) and search(Object) methods, which are abstract methods of this class. The Hashtable class provides methods for initializing the hashtable, computing the hash value for a given object, inserting an object into the hashtable, searching for an object in the hashtable, deleting an object from the hashtable, and rehashing the hashtable if the load factor becomes too low or too high.

    • Method Detail

      • resolveCollision

        public abstract void resolveCollision​(int index,
                                      java.lang.Object value)
        This is an abstract method that needs to be implemented by any class that extends the Hashtable class. It is used to resolve collisions that may occur when inserting a new value into the hashtable. The method takes in two arguments: the index where the collision occurred, and the value that caused the collision. The implementation of the method should resolve the collision according to the specific collision resolution technique used by the hashtable. For example, if linear probing is used, the resolveCollision method should implement linear probing. If chaining is used, the resolveCollision method should implement chaining. The method should not return any value, but should modify the hashtable as needed.
        Parameters:
        index - position where the collision occurred
        value - the value that caused the collision

      • search

        public abstract java.lang.Object search​(java.lang.Object value)
        This method is an abstract method that must be implemented by concrete classes extending the Hashtable abstract class. The method performs a search for a specific value within the Hashtable.
        Parameters:
        value - the value to search for in the Hashtable
        Returns:
        the value found in the Hashtable or null if the value is not found

      • initialize

        public void initialize​(int size)
        Initializes the hashtable with the specified size. It creates a new ArrayList object of the specified size and adds null to each element. This method is used by the constructors to initialize the hashtable.
        Parameters:
        size - the initial size of the hashtable

      • delete

        public boolean delete​(java.lang.Object value)
        Deletes the specified value from the hashtable. Returns false if the value is null or if the value is not found in the hashtable. Otherwise, deletes the value and returns true. First, the method checks if the value is null. If so, it returns false. Then, it searches for the value using the search(Object) method, which returns null if the value is not found in the hashtable. If the value is found, the method deletes it by replacing the value at its corresponding index with the DELETED_VALUE constant. This ensures that the value will not be found again during future searches. If the number of elements in the hashtable becomes less than 25% or greater than 75% of the hashtable's size after deleting the value, the method triggers a rehash to adjust the size of the hashtable accordingly.
        Parameters:
        value - the value to be deleted from the hashtable
        Returns:
        true if the value is successfully deleted, false otherwisen
        See Also:
        search(Object), DELETED_VALUE, rehash(boolean)

      • hash

        public int hash​(java.lang.Object value)
        Returns the hash value for the given object. This is computed as the absolute value of the object's hash code modulo the size of the hash table.
        Parameters:
        value - the object whose hash value is to be computed.
        Returns:
        the hash value of the specified object.
        See Also:
        Object.hashCode(), Math.abs(int), getSize()

      • insert

        public void insert​(java.lang.Object value)
        Inserts the given value into the hash table. If the value is null, nothing happens. If the hash table needs to be rehashed, rehashes the table before inserting. If the value already exists in the hash table, resolves the collision with the existing value by calling the resolveCollision(int, Object) method. Otherwise, inserts the value into the hash table at the index computed by the hash(Object) method. Finally, increments the element count of the hash table by calling the incrementElements() method.
        Parameters:
        value - the object to be inserted into the hash table.
        See Also:
        rehash(boolean), search(Object), resolveCollision(int, Object), hash(Object), set(int, Object), incrementElements()

      • rehashNeeded

        public boolean rehashNeeded()
        Returns a boolean indicating whether the hash table needs to be rehashed. The hash table needs to be rehashed if the number of elements in the table is greater than or equal to 75% of the size of the table or less than or equal to 25% of the size of the table. This ensures that the table is neither too full nor too empty, which optimizes performance and minimizes the chance of collisions.
        Returns:
        true if the hash table needs to be rehashed, false otherwise.

      • rehash

        public void rehash​(boolean increase)
        Rehashes the hash table to increase or decrease its size based on the boolean flag increase. If increase is true, the size of the table is doubled, and if it is false, the size is halved. The elements of the old table are reinserted into the new table after it is initialized.
        Parameters:
        increase - a boolean flag indicating whether to increase or decrease the size of the hash table.
        See Also:
        initialize(int), insert(Object)
